#compdef gofmtmd
# ============================================================================
# gofmtmd - apply gofmt to Go code blocks inside
#            markdown files (Go, Apache-2.0)
#
# Author : po3rin (Hiroki Nakagawa)
# Upstream: https://github.com/po3rin/gofmtmd
#
# `gofmtmd` walks a markdown file, detects fenced
# Go code blocks (```` ```go ```` fences), runs the
# Go standard `gofmt` formatter on each block's
# contents, and writes the formatted result back
# into the markdown. Use cases:
#   - keep Go code samples in documentation
#     consistently formatted as the surrounding
#     code style evolves
#   - lint pull requests against drift between
#     committed Go code + the snippets quoted in
#     README / docs files
#   - integrate into pre-commit hooks for blog posts
#     / talk slides / book manuscripts that embed
#     live Go examples
#
# Usage:
#   gofmtmd [file.md]
#   gofmtmd -r file.md            # rewrite in place
#   gofmtmd -w out.md file.md     # write to out.md
#   cat file.md | gofmtmd         # stdin -> stdout
#
# Flags (cobra):
#   -r, --replace          - replace original Go code
#                             with formatted code
#                             in-place
#   -w, --write <file>     - write the formatted
#                             markdown to <file>
#                             instead of stdout
#   -h, --help             - print help
#   --version              - print version
#
# When invoked without `--replace` or `--write`,
# gofmtmd prints the formatted markdown to stdout
# (suitable for piping through `delta` or `git
# diff --no-index --` for visual diffing).
#
# The sergi/go-diff lane is built on `github.com/
# sergi/go-diff v1.0.0` (declared at upstream
# go.mod HEAD as a direct dep), the canonical Go
# diffing library by Sergi Mansilla - github.com/
# sergi/go-diff, 2000+ stars.
#
# sergi/go-diff is a *line-by-line Go port* of
# Google's `diff-match-patch` library (originally
# written by Neil Fraser at Google in 2006, then
# ported to ~10 languages over the next decade).
# The C++ original implements:
#   - Myers diff (the classic 1986 algorithm)
#   - the patch + merge operations for round-tripping
#     diffs back through the original input
#   - a fast char-grained diff for word-level
#     highlighting in code review tools
#
# The Go port preserves the function-by-function
# correspondence with Google's reference C++ source,
# letting downstream users reason about Go-side
# behavior by reading the C++ algorithm
# documentation. The library is the de-facto Go
# diffing library + the underlying engine for:
#   - hashicorp/terraform's plan output
#   - kubernetes' kubectl diff
#   - cncf/kubectl-ai's diff visualizer
#   - netlify/gotrue's account-change audit log
#   - lacework/go-sdk's resource change reports
#   - gofmtmd (THIS BINARY)
#
# gofmtmd uses sergi/go-diff to compute the per-block
# diff between the original + formatted Go code, then
# only modifies the markdown when the diff is non-
# empty (preserving original line counts + indentation
# for unchanged blocks). The line-grained Myers diff
# gives stable, minimal-edit output.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 252 :: Diffing libraries (Myers / Patience /
#              LCS algorithms with multi-format output)
# Round 1455 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 252
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : mitsuhiko/similar           [R1454 _mdslw]
#   Go      : sergi/go-diff               [R1455 THIS FILE]
#   TS/Node : kpdecker/jsdiff             [R1456 closing]
#
# sergi/go-diff is structurally interesting in this
# axis because of its *Google-reference-port* pattern.
# The three lanes form a clean spectrum of diff-
# library origins:
#
#   - Rust (mitsuhiko/similar): independent multi-
#     algorithm Rust reimplementation by Armin
#     Ronacher; not a port of any specific reference
#     - re-derives the algorithms from the papers +
#     wraps them in idiomatic Rust adapters
#   - Go (sergi/go-diff): line-by-line port of
#     Google's diff-match-patch C++ library; mirrors
#     the upstream API + algorithms; benefits from
#     Google's ongoing maintenance + spec docs
#   - Node (kpdecker/jsdiff): independent pure-JS
#     reimplementation by Kevin Decker (kpdecker);
#     re-derives the algorithms in JS without binding
#     to any reference impl
#
# Cross-language interop happens at the structural
# level - the same input produces the same set of
# inserted / deleted / equal segments across all
# three lanes (modulo equivalent algorithmic choices,
# e.g. all using Myers vs Patience). The output
# formatting differs per lane (similar provides
# unified+side-by-side+inline formatters, go-diff
# provides the patch+match+diff operation triple,
# jsdiff provides line+word+character+JSON diff
# variants), but the underlying diff structure is
# convertible across formats.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - mdslw (Rust, similar): markdown semantic line-
#     wrapper using similar's Myers diff for
#     --report diff output
#   - gofmtmd (Go, sergi/go-diff): gofmt applied to
#     Go code blocks in markdown, using sergi/go-diff
#     to detect + minimize per-block edits
#   - jsdiff consumer (Node, kpdecker/jsdiff): TBD
#     for R1456 closure
#
# Each lane reflects the host ecosystem's diffing
# culture: Rust's "re-derive from papers", Go's
# "port Google's reference", Node's "re-derive in
# JS". All three produce structurally-equivalent
# diffs.
# ============================================================================

_gofmtmd() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-r --replace)'{-r,--replace}'[replace Go code with formatted code in-place]' \
        '(-w --write)'{-w,--write}'[write formatted markdown to file (instead of stdout)]:file:_files -g "*.md"' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)--version[print version]' \
        '1:markdown file:_files -g "*.md"'
}

_gofmtmd "$@"
